2026-04-16 12:33:54 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module negative/return network (ground reference path)'] hypothesis_explanation='All tests show: (1) the PSU is healthy (PSU LED on, 12 V between its + and −); (2) polarity through all inter-module cabling is correct; (3) the relay coil is continuously driven (≈12 V between its coil terminals), and the relay contact itself has very low resistance (0.01 Ω) and passes essentially the full battery voltage from the PSU + to the control output + when measured locally; yet (4) only ≈0.36 V appears between the control output + and the load return/PSU −, and the relay coil/return node sits ≈0.36 V above the true 0 V reference.\n\nThis means the entire ambient sensor module—including its output to the load and the relay’s return—is floating on a pseudo-“ground” that is offset and not actually bonded to the PSU negative. That explains why the lamp remains unlit even though the relay appears to be energized: the 12 V present inside the control module is measured relative to a faulty reference that is not the real 0 V used by the lamp and the PSU.\n\nThe most plausible root cause is a fault in the ambient sensor module’s negative/return network: an open or high-resistance connection between the module’s internal ground node (to which the relay return, output return, and control electronics are tied) and the PSU negative line. This could be a cracked solder joint, broken track, or miswired terminal within the ambient sensor module. Repairing or reworking that ground/return path so the module ground is solidly connected to PSU − should restore proper 12 V at the load and eliminate the abnormal 0.36 V offset and the resulting failure of the lamp to light.'
